<Subpage
  title="You know all your roles by heart. The person underneath them is harder to find."
  lead="Spouse. Parent. Employee. The responsible one. The one who handles things. You could recite the list in your sleep, because you've been living it on repeat for years."
  metaTitle="Coming Back to Yourself — Ennea Evolution"
  metaDescription="The roles got louder than the person underneath them. Coming back into contact with the part of you that got set aside."
  start="You don't have to arrive with answers. You just have to be willing to believe there might still be something worth finding, and willing to start listening for it again. That part, the listening, is the work. We do it together."
>
  <p>But ask what <em>you</em> want, what you'd do with a free Saturday and nobody to answer to, and something strange happens. A pause. Maybe a pull toward something you can't quite name, or a flicker of an answer you talk yourself out of before it fully arrives. Not because there's nothing in you. Because what's in you got set aside so long ago you've lost easy access to it.</p>

  <h3>You might recognize this</h3>
  <ul class="ticklist">
    <li>You keep saying "maybe someday" about things that matter to you.</li>
    <li>Someone asks what you'd do if nothing were expected of you, and the question follows you around for days.</li>
    <li>You catch yourself looking at someone else's life and feeling a pull you can't quite name.</li>
    <li>You get everything done. It just doesn't always feel like you're all the way there while you're doing it.</li>
    <li>There's a faint hollow feeling. The closest word might be homesick, except you never left.</li>
    <li>Wanting more can feel like a betrayal of a perfectly good life, so you keep it to yourself.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>What actually happened</h3>
  <p>Nothing happened to you, exactly. Life happened around you, and you did what each season asked. Kids needed raising, careers needed building, parents needed care, bills needed paying. Every time a want of yours collided with a duty, the duty won, and at the time, it usually had to.</p>
  <p>The strange thing about postponing yourself is that it doesn't feel painful. It feels practical. You turn the volume down on what you want so you can do what you need. But the dial isn't selective. Turn down the wanting often enough and the joy, the color, and the sense of being fully present turn down with it, because they all run on the same dial.</p>
  <p>And here's the part worth being clear about. What gets set aside isn't really the hobbies or the dreams. Those are just where it shows. What gets set aside is your aliveness, the part of you that feels most like you. This work was never about becoming someone new. It's about coming back into contact with the person who was here before the roles became everything. She isn't gone. She's just been waiting for a season that never got scheduled.</p>

  <h3>Turning the volume back up</h3>
  <p>It starts with listening again, not planning. The wanting got quiet slowly, and it comes back slowly: it becomes safe to feel again, a little at a time, and the volume comes up on its own. Things you'd stopped noticing start reaching you.</p>
  <p>The real work is internal, and it's about mattering. Letting yourself count, not someday, now. Taking what you feel and what you want as seriously as you've taken everyone else's needs for years. Coming to understand, somewhere deeper than logic, that supporting the people you love was never supposed to mean disappearing yourself in the process.</p>
  <p>And along the way, the roles become separate from who you are. Not by dropping anything, the life you built is real, and nothing here requires tearing it down. You keep every role you have. You just stop being <em>only</em> them.</p>

  <h3>What changes</h3>
  <p>The volume comes back up. Food tastes like something again, music lands again, and free time stops feeling like a void you should fill with something productive.</p>
  <p>Wants come back with names on them. Your own name starts showing up on your own calendar. And the question circling underneath everything finally comes through clearly: not what's expected of me, but what do I want. You'll have answers. That's the strangest, best part. You always did.</p>
</Subpage>
